        <section xml:id="Section_2_2">
        <title>Section 2.2</title>
        

<subsection xml:id="Question_2_2_1">
    <title> Problem 1</title>
    <p>
        From the division algorithm,  <m>a</m> can be written uniquely as <m>a=bq+r</m> where <m>0 \leq r &lt; b</m>. 
        We'll add and subtract <m>2b</m>:
        <md>
            <mrow>a \amp = bq+r</mrow>
            <mrow>a \amp =(bq-2b)+(2b+r)</mrow>
            <mrow>a \amp =b(q-2)+(2b+r).</mrow>
        </md> 
        For the inequality we have:
        <md>
            <mrow>0 \amp \leq r &lt; b </mrow>
            <mrow>2b \amp \leq r+2b &lt; 3b. </mrow>
        </md>
        
        
    </p>
</subsection>        
            
<subsection xml:id="Question_2_2_2">
<title> Problem 2</title>

<p>
    Suppose <m>n=6k+5</m>. Then, <m>n=3(2k)+3+2=3(2k+1)+2</m> and so <m>n</m> is of the form <m>3j+1</m> where <m>j=2k+1</m>.

    Conversely, for example, <m>m=3 \cdot 0+1=3</m> is not of the form <m>6k+5</m> since <m>6k+5=3</m> has no integer solutions.
</p>

       
</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="Question_2_2_3">
    <title>Problem 3</title>

    <ol marker="(a)">
        <li>

    <p>
        By the division algorithm, any integer, <m>n</m>, is of the form <m>3k</m>, <m>3k+1</m>, or <m>3k+2</m>.

        Square each of these cases:
        <md>
            <mrow>(3k)^2 \amp =9k^2=3(3k^2) </mrow>
            <mrow>(3k+1)^2 \amp = 9k^2+6k+1=3(3k^2+2k)+1 </mrow>
            <mrow>(3k+2)^2 \amp = 9k^2+12k+4=3(3k^2+4k+1)+1.</mrow>
        </md>
      So the square of any integer is of the form <m>3j</m> or <m>3j+1.</m>  
    </p>
</li>

<li>
    <p>
        Any integer, <m>n</m> can be written in the form <m>n=9k+r</m> where <m>0 \leq r &lt; 9.</m>

        Then <me> n^3=9^3k^3+3\cdot 9^2k^2r+3\cdot9kr^2+r^3=9(9^2k^3+3\cdot 9 k^2r+3kr^2)+r^3.</me>  It remains to show that <m>r^3</m> is of the desired form:

        <md>
            <mrow>0^3 \amp =9(0) </mrow>
            <mrow>1^3 \amp =9(0)+1</mrow>
            <mrow>2^3 \amp = 9(0)+8</mrow>
            <mrow>3^3 \amp =9(3)</mrow>
            <mrow>4^3 \amp =64=9(7)+1</mrow>
            <mrow>5^3 \amp =125 = 9(13)+8</mrow>
            <mrow>6^3 \amp =216 = 9(24)+0</mrow>
            <mrow>7^3 \amp =343 = 9(38)+1</mrow>
            <mrow>8^3 \amp= 512 =9(56)+8.</mrow>
        </md>
        
        
        
        
        
            
        
    </p>
</li>
</ol>
</subsection>
    
<subsection xml:id="Question_2_2_4">
    <title>Problem 4</title>
<p>
    If <m>a</m> is an integer then <m>a^2</m> is of the form <m>3k</m> or <m>3k+1</m> by problem 3a. If <m>a=3k</m> then:
    <md>
        <mrow>3a^2-1 \amp =3(3k)^2-1</mrow>
    </md>
     which is neither of the form  <m>3k</m> or <m>3k+1</m>.  (It is of the form <m>3k+2</m>.)
     If <m>a=3k+1 </m>  then:
     <md>
        3a^2-1=3(3k+1)^2-1=27k^2+18k+2=3(9k^2+6k)+2.
     </md>

     Again, this is neither of the form <m>3k</m> or <m>3k+1</m>.

    Since <m>3a^2-1</m> is never of the form <m>3k</m> or <m>3k+1</m> it cannot be a square.
     
</p>

</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="Question_2_2_6">
    <title>Problem 6</title>
    <p>
        Let <m>n=7q+r</m> by the division algorithm.  There are 6 cases.  
        Below the results are shown for some <m>k</m>.  For example on the first line <m>k=49q^3</m>.
        <md>
            <mrow>(7q)^3 \amp= 7(49q^3)=7k</mrow>
            <mrow>(7q+1)^3 \amp = 7k+1</mrow>
            <mrow> (7q+2)^3 \amp =7k+1</mrow>
            <mrow> (7q+3)^3 \amp  =7k+6=7\hat{k}-1</mrow>
            <mrow>(7q+4)^3 \amp =7k+1</mrow>
            <mrow>(7q+5)^3 \amp = 7k+6=7\hat{k}-1 </mrow>
            <mrow>(7q+6)^3 \amp =7k+6=7\hat{k}-1.</mrow>
        </md>
    </p>
</subsection>



    <subsection xml:id="Question_9">
    <title>Problem 9</title>

    <p>
        Let <m>n \in \mathbb{Z}</m> and write <m>n=7q+r</m> where <m>0 \leq r &lt; 7</m>.  
        Consider the squares in each of the cases: (<m>k</m> represents some integer below. For example <m>k</m> would be <m>7q^2</m> in the first line.)
        <md>
            <mrow>(7q)^2 \amp= 7(7q^2)</mrow>
            <mrow>(7q+1)^2 \amp = 7k+1</mrow>
            <mrow> (7q+2)^2 \amp =7k+4</mrow>
            <mrow> (7q+3)^2 \amp  =7k+2</mrow>
            <mrow>(7q+4)^2 \amp =7k+2</mrow>
            <mrow>(7q+5)^2 \amp = 7k+4 </mrow>
            <mrow>(7q+6)^2 \amp =7k+1.</mrow>
        </md>
        And, similarly, the cubes:
        <md>
            <mrow>(7q)^3 \amp= 7(49q^3)</mrow>
            <mrow>(7q+1)^3 \amp = 7k+1</mrow>
            <mrow> (7q+2)^3 \amp =7k+1</mrow>
            <mrow> (7q+3)^3 \amp  =7k+6</mrow>
            <mrow>(7q+4)^3 \amp =7k+1</mrow>
            <mrow>(7q+5)^3 \amp = 7k+6 </mrow>
            <mrow>(7q+6)^3 \amp =7k+6.</mrow>
        </md>
        So, squares of integers are of the form <m>7k</m>, <m>7k+1</m>, <m>7k+2</m>, or <m>7k+4</m>. 
        Cubes are of the form <m>7k</m>, <m>7k+1</m>, or <m>7k+6</m>. 
        If an integer is both a square and a cube it must be of the form <m>7k</m> or <m>7k+1</m>.

        


        
    </p>
    </subsection>

     <subsection sml:id="Question_2_2_10">
    <title>Problem 10</title>
    <p>
        There are 6 cases.  We'll illustrate here with one case: say <m>n=6l+2</m>. 
        Rather than deal with the entire expression let's try to build one piece at a time:
        <md>
            <mrow>n^2 \amp =(6l+2)^2=6j+4 \text{ for some } j</mrow>
            <mrow>7n^2 \amp = 7(6j+4)=6s+4 \text{ for some } s</mrow>
            <mrow> 7n^2+5 \amp =7(6s+4) +5 = 6t+3 \text{ for some } t </mrow>
            <mrow> n(7n^2+5) \amp= (6l+2)(6t+3) =6u \text{ for some } u.</mrow>
        </md>
        
        This proves the result. It's a bit tedious to find each of the integers <m>j,s,t,u</m> but not computationally difficult. 
        For this problem we are only concerned that such integers exist, not what they are.
        
    </p>

     </subsection>

